WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.440 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:04.392 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.392 --> 00:00:07.808 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.808 --> 00:00:14.460 align:middle line:90%


00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:16.560 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
OK, so last time we

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:19.300 align:middle line:90%
were looking at a metric space.

00:00:19.300 --> 00:00:20.470 align:middle line:90%
So this is a metric space.

00:00:20.470 --> 00:00:25.840 align:middle line:90%


00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:30.830 align:middle line:84%
And we looked at what
we called a open subset.

00:00:30.830 --> 00:00:37.920 align:middle line:90%


00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:42.240 align:middle line:84%
And so an open subset
is-- so over here

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:59.710 align:middle line:84%
is now a subset of x is said
to be open if for all x in O

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:12.030 align:middle line:84%
there exists r greater than 0
so that the entire ball around x

00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:14.470 align:middle line:90%
is contained in O.

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:20.510 align:middle line:84%
And so the picture is
that here you have x.

00:01:20.510 --> 00:01:23.950 align:middle line:84%
Here you have some
open subset O.

00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:29.710 align:middle line:84%
And so if for each
point x in O, there

00:01:29.710 --> 00:01:36.150 align:middle line:84%
is an entire ball here
that is contained in O,

00:01:36.150 --> 00:01:37.960 align:middle line:90%
then O is said to be open.

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:42.470 align:middle line:90%


00:01:42.470 --> 00:01:46.970 align:middle line:84%
One of a few things
that we proved is--

00:01:46.970 --> 00:01:51.873 align:middle line:90%
so one thing we proved is that--

00:01:51.873 --> 00:01:54.910 align:middle line:90%


00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:56.850 align:middle line:84%
so again, x, d is
a metric space.

00:01:56.850 --> 00:01:59.400 align:middle line:90%


00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:08.380 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, I should say we
defined the ball, Br of x.

00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:14.060 align:middle line:90%
So here, x is in x.

00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:16.460 align:middle line:90%
r is some positive number.

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:23.260 align:middle line:84%
And then this thing here
is then the y in x such

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:31.740 align:middle line:84%
that the distance from x to
y is strictly less than r.

00:02:31.740 --> 00:02:41.410 align:middle line:84%
And we showed that
Br of x is given.

00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:44.020 align:middle line:90%


00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:47.780 align:middle line:84%
By that Br, we say
also that Br of x

00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:56.750 align:middle line:84%
is a ball of radius
r centered at x.

00:02:56.750 --> 00:03:05.570 align:middle line:90%


00:03:05.570 --> 00:03:10.390 align:middle line:84%
Now, there's a few other
things that we discussed.

00:03:10.390 --> 00:03:13.650 align:middle line:90%


00:03:13.650 --> 00:03:24.330 align:middle line:84%
So one thing is
that so on subsets,

00:03:24.330 --> 00:03:26.150 align:middle line:90%
we have three operations.

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:37.610 align:middle line:90%


00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:39.310 align:middle line:90%
One is intersection.

00:03:39.310 --> 00:03:44.570 align:middle line:90%


00:03:44.570 --> 00:04:00.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is that if u alpha
is a family of subsets, then

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:05.570 align:middle line:84%
we look at the intersection
of all these subsets.

00:04:05.570 --> 00:04:10.290 align:middle line:84%
And so x is in this
intersection just

00:04:10.290 --> 00:04:16.720 align:middle line:84%
means that x is in u
alpha for all alpha.

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:21.209 align:middle line:90%


00:04:21.209 --> 00:04:27.010 align:middle line:84%
The second operation
we looked at was union.

00:04:27.010 --> 00:04:31.570 align:middle line:84%
And so again, u alpha
is a family of subsets.

00:04:31.570 --> 00:04:38.210 align:middle line:84%
Then we say that x here is
in the union of the u alpha.

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:50.370 align:middle line:84%
This is the same as saying that
there exists alpha such that x

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:53.640 align:middle line:90%
is in u alpha.

00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:56.440 align:middle line:90%
And the third thing we--

00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:01.920 align:middle line:84%
the celebration we have is that
if you have a subset capital

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:07.500 align:middle line:90%
U, then we have the complement.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:21.760 align:middle line:84%
So the complement
of U is the x such

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:27.860 align:middle line:84%
that x is not in U.
That's a complement.

00:05:27.860 --> 00:05:33.360 align:middle line:84%
And so there was these
three operations on subsets.

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:37.280 align:middle line:90%
And why this is relevant here?

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:43.360 align:middle line:84%
This is relevant
because if u alpha--

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:46.150 align:middle line:90%
so we have the following lemma.

00:05:46.150 --> 00:05:51.470 align:middle line:90%


00:05:51.470 --> 00:05:53.710 align:middle line:84%
Again, we have a
metric space here,

00:05:53.710 --> 00:06:10.630 align:middle line:84%
and we have O alpha is a
family of open subset of x.

00:06:10.630 --> 00:06:17.640 align:middle line:90%
Then the union is also open.

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:21.310 align:middle line:90%


00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:23.920 align:middle line:90%
Now why is this the case?

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:28.070 align:middle line:90%


00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:35.470 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's the case
because if x here

00:06:35.470 --> 00:06:40.630 align:middle line:84%
is in the union of
the O alpha, then

00:06:40.630 --> 00:06:50.380 align:middle line:84%
this means that there exists
alpha such that x here

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:53.340 align:middle line:90%
is in alpha.

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:58.860 align:middle line:84%
But since that alpha is open,
this means that there exists--

00:06:58.860 --> 00:07:01.060 align:middle line:84%
so not only is x
in that, but there

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:14.060 align:middle line:84%
exists r that depends on
x and alpha r positive,

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:22.380 align:middle line:84%
so that the whole ball centered
at x is contained in O alpha.

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:26.210 align:middle line:84%
But if it's contained in
alpha then this imply--

00:07:26.210 --> 00:07:32.180 align:middle line:90%


00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:39.420 align:middle line:84%
if it's contained
in alpha, then this

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:42.100 align:middle line:84%
implies that it's,
of course, this ball

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:49.960 align:middle line:84%
here is contained in
the union of these guys.

00:07:49.960 --> 00:07:53.450 align:middle line:90%


00:07:53.450 --> 00:07:57.490 align:middle line:84%
But that's exactly
what it means,

00:07:57.490 --> 00:07:59.620 align:middle line:90%
to say that the union is open.

00:07:59.620 --> 00:08:07.890 align:middle line:90%


00:08:07.890 --> 00:08:13.810 align:middle line:84%
The other lemma
related to this is--

00:08:13.810 --> 00:08:16.890 align:middle line:84%
and there, you
have to be careful

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:20.270 align:middle line:90%
that if you have finitely many.

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:28.290 align:middle line:84%
So can you have a
metric space and O1 up

00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:37.540 align:middle line:84%
to On finitely
many open subsets?

00:08:37.540 --> 00:08:43.650 align:middle line:90%


00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:48.160 align:middle line:84%
If you have finitely
many open subsets,

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:54.500 align:middle line:84%
then the intersection
of these is also open.

00:08:54.500 --> 00:09:00.520 align:middle line:90%


00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:03.560 align:middle line:90%
Now why is that the case?

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:09.360 align:middle line:84%
This is the case
because if you have--

00:09:09.360 --> 00:09:18.760 align:middle line:84%
so if x here is in the
intersection of these guys,

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:23.480 align:middle line:84%
then it means that this is
equivalent to saying that x here

00:09:23.480 --> 00:09:26.180 align:middle line:90%
is in z for all i--

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:28.960 align:middle line:90%


00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:30.860 align:middle line:90%
i equal to 1 up to n.

00:09:30.860 --> 00:09:37.960 align:middle line:90%


00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:48.510 align:middle line:84%
But since Oi is open, then
for Oi, there exists ri.

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:59.230 align:middle line:84%
This means that since Oi is
open, there exists at ri such

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:11.790 align:middle line:84%
that the ball here with radius
r but center x, this one here

00:10:11.790 --> 00:10:12.990 align:middle line:90%
is contained in Oi.

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:15.590 align:middle line:90%


00:10:15.590 --> 00:10:17.950 align:middle line:90%
This is for each i.

00:10:17.950 --> 00:10:20.750 align:middle line:84%
But now if we check--
there's only finitely many

00:10:20.750 --> 00:10:27.040 align:middle line:84%
i so you can let r be the
minimum of these guys.

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:30.230 align:middle line:90%


00:10:30.230 --> 00:10:35.710 align:middle line:84%
If r is the minimum
of these guys, then

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:38.530 align:middle line:90%
the ball of radius r around x--

00:10:38.530 --> 00:10:42.710 align:middle line:84%
these are the points where the
distance is strictly less than r

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:44.260 align:middle line:90%
to x.

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:50.620 align:middle line:84%
But that is, of course,
contained in Br i of x.

00:10:50.620 --> 00:10:53.540 align:middle line:84%
This is for each
i, you have this.

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:59.020 align:middle line:84%
But this one here was supposed
to be contained in Oi.

00:10:59.020 --> 00:11:04.700 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
this ball here--

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:15.460 align:middle line:84%
again, this ball here is
contained in this for each i.

00:11:15.460 --> 00:11:17.500 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this ball must

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:22.130 align:middle line:84%
be contained in the
intersection of these guys.

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:26.020 align:middle line:90%


00:11:26.020 --> 00:11:28.960 align:middle line:84%
And I'll just
write it out again,

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:36.940 align:middle line:84%
just emphasizing that I'm only
doing this for finitely many Os.

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:39.500 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly
what it means,

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:41.860 align:middle line:90%
that the intersection is open.

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:45.580 align:middle line:84%
And again, you could draw
a little picture here.

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:48.100 align:middle line:84%
It might be helpful to
draw a little picture.

00:11:48.100 --> 00:11:52.860 align:middle line:90%
You have this here is O1.

00:11:52.860 --> 00:11:55.700 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have O2.

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:58.220 align:middle line:90%
And here, you have O3.

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:01.380 align:middle line:84%
You have a point in
the intersection.

00:12:01.380 --> 00:12:04.940 align:middle line:84%
There's a ball here that
is contained in this.

00:12:04.940 --> 00:12:09.100 align:middle line:84%
There's another ball here
that's contained in this.

00:12:09.100 --> 00:12:11.940 align:middle line:84%
And there's a third
ball, this ball here.

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:14.500 align:middle line:90%
So that's contained in that.

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:17.860 align:middle line:84%
And then you look at
the smallest ball.

00:12:17.860 --> 00:12:21.340 align:middle line:84%
You look at the smallest
weight-- the minimum, again,

00:12:21.340 --> 00:12:23.780 align:middle line:90%
of the radii.

00:12:23.780 --> 00:12:30.180 align:middle line:84%
And that ball is then contained
in the intersection of the 3.

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:36.980 align:middle line:90%


00:12:36.980 --> 00:12:39.080 align:middle line:84%
Now why do we have
to be careful?

00:12:39.080 --> 00:12:43.090 align:middle line:84%
Let me just remind you, why
do we have to be careful here?

00:12:43.090 --> 00:12:47.930 align:middle line:84%
And so the examples that
we looked at last time

00:12:47.930 --> 00:13:00.650 align:middle line:90%
was that if you are on--

00:13:00.650 --> 00:13:07.490 align:middle line:84%
so the example from last
time is that if x here

00:13:07.490 --> 00:13:14.026 align:middle line:84%
is the real number and
you're looking at On--

00:13:14.026 --> 00:13:18.610 align:middle line:90%
n here is a natural number--

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:25.010 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at this
interval here from minus 1

00:13:25.010 --> 00:13:30.010 align:middle line:84%
over n to n, well,
then if you're

00:13:30.010 --> 00:13:36.150 align:middle line:84%
looking at the intersection
of all of these,

00:13:36.150 --> 00:13:39.470 align:middle line:90%
well, that's just the one point.

00:13:39.470 --> 00:13:42.640 align:middle line:90%


00:13:42.640 --> 00:13:46.220 align:middle line:84%
And of course, 0 is
not an open subset.

00:13:46.220 --> 00:13:49.200 align:middle line:84%
Because if it was an open
subset, a whole ball--

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:52.680 align:middle line:84%
and a ball here on the
line is like a little open

00:13:52.680 --> 00:13:55.620 align:middle line:84%
little interval that doesn't
have the two endpoints.

00:13:55.620 --> 00:13:58.180 align:middle line:90%


00:13:58.180 --> 00:14:11.520 align:middle line:84%
So note that in this example,
each Oi or each On is open,

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:20.670 align:middle line:84%
but the intersection of
the On's is not open.

00:14:20.670 --> 00:14:23.880 align:middle line:90%


00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:28.200 align:middle line:84%
And the problem, again, is
that there are infinitely many

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:28.760 align:middle line:90%
of n's.

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:32.000 align:middle line:90%


00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:37.070 align:middle line:84%
Now again, one of the
things we proved was--

00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:42.470 align:middle line:84%
and maybe I was just
here on that board--

00:14:42.470 --> 00:14:45.670 align:middle line:84%
but one of the things
we proved last time

00:14:45.670 --> 00:14:53.920 align:middle line:84%
was that if you take a ball,
then it is actually an open set.

00:14:53.920 --> 00:14:58.910 align:middle line:90%


00:14:58.910 --> 00:15:10.230 align:middle line:84%
Let me prove a
variation of that.

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:16.030 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you're looking at--
so let's have a lemma here

00:15:16.030 --> 00:15:19.830 align:middle line:84%
that if you have, again,
a metric space here

00:15:19.830 --> 00:15:22.830 align:middle line:90%
and r here is bigger than 0.

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:28.230 align:middle line:84%
Now let's look at the
x and then take away.

00:15:28.230 --> 00:15:30.490 align:middle line:90%
But now I'm looking at the sets.

00:15:30.490 --> 00:15:34.030 align:middle line:84%
So let me look at
the set y here.

00:15:34.030 --> 00:15:41.300 align:middle line:84%
So x is some fixed point
in this metric space,

00:15:41.300 --> 00:15:52.340 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at the y in x
so that the distance to x from y

00:15:52.340 --> 00:15:55.300 align:middle line:90%
is strictly bigger than r.

00:15:55.300 --> 00:16:06.300 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, if this
here is x, this is the space x.

00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:08.540 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have the point x.

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:14.060 align:middle line:84%
Then you have here this,
including this circle here,

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:17.820 align:middle line:84%
are the points that
have distance at most r

00:16:17.820 --> 00:16:20.500 align:middle line:90%
from little x.

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:27.140 align:middle line:84%
Then this is the set
here outside this disk,

00:16:27.140 --> 00:16:32.740 align:middle line:84%
where the boundary is
included, so outside.

00:16:32.740 --> 00:16:37.210 align:middle line:84%
And so what I want to prove
here is that this here

00:16:37.210 --> 00:16:40.640 align:middle line:90%
is this here is an open subset.

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:44.810 align:middle line:90%


00:16:44.810 --> 00:16:48.170 align:middle line:84%
And the proof is
very similar to how

00:16:48.170 --> 00:16:50.910 align:middle line:90%
we proved that a ball is open.

00:16:50.910 --> 00:16:59.290 align:middle line:84%
Again, the key ingredient
is the triangle inequality.

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:12.410 align:middle line:90%
And so let's try to prove that.

00:17:12.410 --> 00:17:26.710 align:middle line:84%
So we take y here in this--
let's call this set something.

00:17:26.710 --> 00:17:32.280 align:middle line:90%
Let's call it E.

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:36.960 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you have
x here, y here in E.

00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:41.720 align:middle line:84%
So this means that the
distance from y to x

00:17:41.720 --> 00:17:44.760 align:middle line:90%
is strictly bigger than r.

00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:47.260 align:middle line:90%
I want to prove--

00:17:47.260 --> 00:17:51.720 align:middle line:90%
so I have my picture here.

00:17:51.720 --> 00:17:52.700 align:middle line:90%
This is x.

00:17:52.700 --> 00:17:54.680 align:middle line:90%
This is this ball here.

00:17:54.680 --> 00:17:58.080 align:middle line:84%
And then I have a y
that lie outside it.

00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:01.160 align:middle line:84%
And I want to find
a little ball here

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:04.720 align:middle line:84%
around y that is
entirely contained

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:07.400 align:middle line:90%
in the complement of this ball.

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:12.920 align:middle line:84%
And so I do the same
that I did last time--

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:16.280 align:middle line:84%
I mean, almost the same,
not exactly the same.

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:19.500 align:middle line:90%
So we said S here equal to y.

00:18:19.500 --> 00:18:23.200 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is that you're
looking at this distance here.

00:18:23.200 --> 00:18:27.240 align:middle line:90%
This distance is d x, y.

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:32.040 align:middle line:90%
This part of it is r.

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:38.160 align:middle line:84%
And so it seems reasonable, this
here, if this picture was right,

00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:42.720 align:middle line:90%
then this thing here would be s.

00:18:42.720 --> 00:18:50.200 align:middle line:84%
And this s here would
be d x, y minus r.

00:18:50.200 --> 00:18:54.580 align:middle line:84%
So that's what I'm
setting s equal to.

00:18:54.580 --> 00:18:58.000 align:middle line:90%


00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.920 align:middle line:84%
And the first thing I noticed
that because this is strictly

00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:06.400 align:middle line:84%
bigger than r, this thing
here is strictly positive.

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:11.840 align:middle line:84%
And then I take set
here in that ball.

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:13.840 align:middle line:90%
Now it's centered at y.

00:19:13.840 --> 00:19:16.880 align:middle line:90%
Let's have radius s.

00:19:16.880 --> 00:19:22.240 align:middle line:84%
And then I want to look
at the distance to--

00:19:22.240 --> 00:19:23.860 align:middle line:90%
and I want to estimate.

00:19:23.860 --> 00:19:44.470 align:middle line:84%
So I want to estimate from
below the distance from x to z.

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:46.375 align:middle line:84%
Well, the triangle
inequality, if you just

00:19:46.375 --> 00:19:47.750 align:middle line:84%
think about the
triangle-- that's

00:19:47.750 --> 00:19:51.250 align:middle line:84%
something like bounding
a distance from above.

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:54.150 align:middle line:84%
So if I want to estimate
something below,

00:19:54.150 --> 00:19:58.430 align:middle line:84%
then basically, this thing I
want to estimate from below

00:19:58.430 --> 00:20:01.550 align:middle line:84%
have to be on the other
side of the inequality.

00:20:01.550 --> 00:20:05.450 align:middle line:90%
And so how does that work?

00:20:05.450 --> 00:20:09.230 align:middle line:90%


00:20:09.230 --> 00:20:14.390 align:middle line:84%
So let's again draw a
little picture, too.

00:20:14.390 --> 00:20:17.870 align:middle line:84%
So let me do a little
bit on the side.

00:20:17.870 --> 00:20:24.270 align:middle line:84%
So I have this ball here,
and I have this y here,

00:20:24.270 --> 00:20:26.010 align:middle line:90%
and then I have this z here.

00:20:26.010 --> 00:20:30.180 align:middle line:90%


00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:32.540 align:middle line:90%
And I now want to say--

00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:35.980 align:middle line:90%
I want to estimate.

00:20:35.980 --> 00:20:42.220 align:middle line:84%
So I'm saying that
the distance from--

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:48.980 align:middle line:84%
so this is what I want
to bound from below.

00:20:48.980 --> 00:20:54.340 align:middle line:84%
And what I know is
that this set here is--

00:20:54.340 --> 00:20:59.020 align:middle line:84%
I know something about
the distance to y.

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:02.420 align:middle line:90%
So this here, I know.

00:21:02.420 --> 00:21:06.820 align:middle line:84%
And so you see, this thing
here by the triangle inequality

00:21:06.820 --> 00:21:15.220 align:middle line:84%
is now bounded by the
distance from x to y.

00:21:15.220 --> 00:21:20.540 align:middle line:84%
And I know that
this thing here is

00:21:20.540 --> 00:21:24.380 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal to this here
is the one I want to estimate.

00:21:24.380 --> 00:21:26.010 align:middle line:90%
So I'm just leaving that.

00:21:26.010 --> 00:21:29.970 align:middle line:84%
This one here, it's because
set is in the ball of radius

00:21:29.970 --> 00:21:31.530 align:middle line:90%
s around y.

00:21:31.530 --> 00:21:39.690 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is actually
strictly less than s, like that.

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:43.090 align:middle line:90%


00:21:43.090 --> 00:21:46.050 align:middle line:84%
And so now you can just
move this one here over

00:21:46.050 --> 00:21:47.450 align:middle line:90%
on the other side.

00:21:47.450 --> 00:21:58.010 align:middle line:84%
And you have that d x, y minus
s is strictly less than d x

00:21:58.010 --> 00:21:59.930 align:middle line:90%
comma z.

00:21:59.930 --> 00:22:03.290 align:middle line:84%
Now we have to
fill in what S is.

00:22:03.290 --> 00:22:05.370 align:middle line:90%
S is up there.

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:10.010 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is-- this thing here

00:22:10.010 --> 00:22:12.710 align:middle line:90%
is equal to this is dx.

00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:14.590 align:middle line:90%
I'm just copying that.

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:21.710 align:middle line:84%
But I fill in what s is,
and s is d x, y minus r.

00:22:21.710 --> 00:22:25.360 align:middle line:90%


00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:29.080 align:middle line:84%
But you see, those two cancel,
and you're left with the r.

00:22:29.080 --> 00:22:31.320 align:middle line:84%
And so you have
that r is strictly

00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:35.440 align:middle line:84%
less than this, which is
exactly what we wanted to prove.

00:22:35.440 --> 00:22:41.640 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, it was almost
exactly the same proof

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:44.180 align:middle line:84%
that we had to prove
that the ball was open.

00:22:44.180 --> 00:22:49.360 align:middle line:90%


00:22:49.360 --> 00:22:51.760 align:middle line:84%
What we're using here
is that, again, we're

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:54.720 align:middle line:84%
using that the
triangle inequality is

00:22:54.720 --> 00:22:57.800 align:middle line:84%
like you're bounding
some distance from above.

00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:02.800 align:middle line:84%
And so you have to use it the
other way with having the things

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:05.800 align:middle line:84%
that you want to bound from
below on the other side

00:23:05.800 --> 00:23:06.980 align:middle line:90%
of the inequality.

00:23:06.980 --> 00:23:09.720 align:middle line:90%


00:23:09.720 --> 00:23:14.160 align:middle line:84%
So the next thing is then-- and
we talked a little bit about

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:16.160 align:middle line:90%
that last time--

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:19.480 align:middle line:84%
the next thing is
closed subsets.

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:23.150 align:middle line:84%
So this may seem
like a triviality

00:23:23.150 --> 00:23:29.110 align:middle line:84%
because it's defined,
in a way, trivially.

00:23:29.110 --> 00:23:30.150 align:middle line:90%
So what is it?

00:23:30.150 --> 00:23:32.960 align:middle line:84%
But it's actually a
really useful notion.

00:23:32.960 --> 00:23:37.390 align:middle line:90%


00:23:37.390 --> 00:23:38.650 align:middle line:90%
And so this is--

00:23:38.650 --> 00:23:42.670 align:middle line:90%


00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:50.890 align:middle line:84%
so a subset C is
said to be closed--

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:52.590 align:middle line:90%
again, x is a metric space--

00:23:52.590 --> 00:24:04.970 align:middle line:84%
to be closed if the
complement is open.

00:24:04.970 --> 00:24:07.670 align:middle line:90%


00:24:07.670 --> 00:24:12.030 align:middle line:84%
So that's how you
define a closed subset.

00:24:12.030 --> 00:24:22.140 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, as we observed,
since the empty set and x are

00:24:22.140 --> 00:24:31.980 align:middle line:84%
both open, the complement of
the empty set is the whole set.

00:24:31.980 --> 00:24:35.460 align:middle line:84%
So it means that x and the
complement of the whole set

00:24:35.460 --> 00:24:36.820 align:middle line:90%
is the empty set.

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:40.340 align:middle line:84%
It means that those
sets are both open--

00:24:40.340 --> 00:24:43.490 align:middle line:90%
are also both closed.

00:24:43.490 --> 00:24:55.660 align:middle line:90%


00:24:55.660 --> 00:25:01.900 align:middle line:84%
So now there is another
way-- you could have defined

00:25:01.900 --> 00:25:04.700 align:middle line:90%
a closed subset another way.

00:25:04.700 --> 00:25:08.120 align:middle line:84%
And this is because you have
the following statement here.

00:25:08.120 --> 00:25:14.620 align:middle line:90%


00:25:14.620 --> 00:25:29.850 align:middle line:84%
So a subset-- you have the
following theorem that, again,

00:25:29.850 --> 00:25:32.130 align:middle line:90%
you have a metric space.

00:25:32.130 --> 00:25:47.090 align:middle line:84%
And C here, subset of x,
is closed if and only if

00:25:47.090 --> 00:25:52.410 align:middle line:90%
for all sequences in C--

00:25:52.410 --> 00:26:12.450 align:middle line:84%
if and only if for
all sequences xn where

00:26:12.450 --> 00:26:20.810 align:middle line:84%
xn is in C, if you have all
sequences, all, let's say,

00:26:20.810 --> 00:26:22.310 align:middle line:90%
convergent sequences--

00:26:22.310 --> 00:26:28.250 align:middle line:90%


00:26:28.250 --> 00:26:36.730 align:middle line:84%
so all convergent sequence
where the sequence lie in C,

00:26:36.730 --> 00:26:55.190 align:middle line:90%
then the limit x is also in C.

00:26:55.190 --> 00:27:00.770 align:middle line:84%
So I claim that if you want
to check that a set is closed,

00:27:00.770 --> 00:27:03.770 align:middle line:84%
instead of checking that
the complement is open,

00:27:03.770 --> 00:27:06.330 align:middle line:90%
you could check that.

00:27:06.330 --> 00:27:09.370 align:middle line:84%
And this seems like
if you were literally

00:27:09.370 --> 00:27:14.010 align:middle line:84%
going to check it on any given
example, explicit example,

00:27:14.010 --> 00:27:16.040 align:middle line:90%
you would never do it this way.

00:27:16.040 --> 00:27:18.540 align:middle line:84%
But it's very useful
for proving things.

00:27:18.540 --> 00:27:23.480 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is that instead
of proving that a complement is

00:27:23.480 --> 00:27:25.720 align:middle line:84%
open, instead you
could just prove

00:27:25.720 --> 00:27:30.000 align:middle line:84%
that whenever you have
a sequence in that set,

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.060 align:middle line:84%
then is the limit
also in that set?

00:27:34.060 --> 00:27:36.640 align:middle line:84%
If that's the case
for all sequences,

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:38.840 align:middle line:90%
then the set is closed.

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:42.820 align:middle line:84%
And so we need to-- so
let's try to prove that.

00:27:42.820 --> 00:27:47.700 align:middle line:84%
And again, it's
useful theoretically.

00:27:47.700 --> 00:27:53.320 align:middle line:84%
But in practice, this
would be totally useless.

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.330 align:middle line:84%
But it is useful
to proving things.

00:27:55.330 --> 00:27:57.920 align:middle line:90%


00:27:57.920 --> 00:28:03.050 align:middle line:84%
And so there's two
things we need to prove.

00:28:03.050 --> 00:28:07.480 align:middle line:90%


00:28:07.480 --> 00:28:09.000 align:middle line:90%
So there's two directions.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:21.360 align:middle line:84%
So assume first
that C is closed.

00:28:21.360 --> 00:28:30.310 align:middle line:90%


00:28:30.310 --> 00:28:39.100 align:middle line:84%
And let xn in C be a
convergent sequence.

00:28:39.100 --> 00:28:46.310 align:middle line:90%


00:28:46.310 --> 00:29:19.420 align:middle line:84%
We want to show that the
limit x is also in C.

00:29:19.420 --> 00:29:43.220 align:middle line:84%
Since xn converges to x, then
for all r greater than 0,

00:29:43.220 --> 00:29:58.460 align:middle line:84%
there exists xn in the ball
here of radius r around

00:29:58.460 --> 00:30:00.920 align:middle line:90%
x because it's converging.

00:30:00.920 --> 00:30:08.620 align:middle line:84%
So this means that for
each r, you must have this.

00:30:08.620 --> 00:30:10.590 align:middle line:90%
But now you see that.

00:30:10.590 --> 00:30:29.570 align:middle line:84%
And if x was not in C, if x is
not in C, since c is closed,

00:30:29.570 --> 00:30:32.540 align:middle line:90%
the complement is open.

00:30:32.540 --> 00:30:35.130 align:middle line:90%


00:30:35.130 --> 00:30:40.310 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that now x is
assumed to be in a complement.

00:30:40.310 --> 00:30:43.130 align:middle line:84%
But that means that
there exists some r

00:30:43.130 --> 00:30:49.290 align:middle line:84%
so that the ball here
of radius of that r

00:30:49.290 --> 00:30:52.310 align:middle line:84%
would be contained
in the complement.

00:30:52.310 --> 00:31:00.150 align:middle line:90%


00:31:00.150 --> 00:31:04.930 align:middle line:84%
But this means that there
is no xn in that ball

00:31:04.930 --> 00:31:09.440 align:middle line:84%
because all of
the xn's are in C.

00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:12.380 align:middle line:84%
And this here is entirely
contained in the complement.

00:31:12.380 --> 00:31:15.980 align:middle line:90%


00:31:15.980 --> 00:31:18.060 align:middle line:90%
So this is the contradiction.

00:31:18.060 --> 00:31:23.480 align:middle line:84%
So if it is closed and you
have a convergent sequence,

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:26.680 align:middle line:84%
that sequence is lying
in this closed set,

00:31:26.680 --> 00:31:33.340 align:middle line:84%
then the limit must be
also contained in the set

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:35.520 align:middle line:84%
because, otherwise,
there would be--

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:38.000 align:middle line:84%
the limit would lie
outside, and there would be

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.260 align:middle line:90%
a little ball centered at that.

00:31:40.260 --> 00:31:44.840 align:middle line:84%
So there was no element in the
sequence that was in that ball.

00:31:44.840 --> 00:31:49.960 align:middle line:84%
But then that sequence couldn't
converge to the center.

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:51.320 align:middle line:90%
And the other thing--

00:31:51.320 --> 00:31:52.980 align:middle line:90%
so this is one direction.

00:31:52.980 --> 00:32:03.120 align:middle line:84%
The other direction that we
need to prove is that if--

00:32:03.120 --> 00:32:05.360 align:middle line:90%
again, it's useless.

00:32:05.360 --> 00:32:07.520 align:middle line:84%
You would never
go about to prove

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:10.310 align:middle line:84%
that a set is closed
in an example,

00:32:10.310 --> 00:32:14.510 align:middle line:84%
but it is useful
more theoretically.

00:32:14.510 --> 00:32:17.630 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you
have a set, and you

00:32:17.630 --> 00:32:22.710 align:middle line:84%
knew that whenever you have
a sequence in that set,

00:32:22.710 --> 00:32:25.870 align:middle line:84%
then the limit that
is convergent--

00:32:25.870 --> 00:32:30.050 align:middle line:84%
then the limit is
also in the set.

00:32:30.050 --> 00:32:38.818 align:middle line:84%
So we also need to show
the converse and, again,

00:32:38.818 --> 00:32:39.360 align:middle line:90%
the converse.

00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:43.270 align:middle line:90%


00:32:43.270 --> 00:33:06.310 align:middle line:84%
So we need to show that if
for all sequences xn with line

00:33:06.310 --> 00:33:34.390 align:middle line:84%
C n is convergent, then the
limit x is also in C. Then

00:33:34.390 --> 00:33:41.650 align:middle line:90%
C is in fact closed.

00:33:41.650 --> 00:33:43.090 align:middle line:90%
So that would be the converse.

00:33:43.090 --> 00:33:47.570 align:middle line:84%
So we prove if and only
if it has this property.

00:33:47.570 --> 00:33:50.390 align:middle line:90%
So now let's assume that--

00:33:50.390 --> 00:33:57.070 align:middle line:84%
so suppose we have this property
that all convergent sequences

00:33:57.070 --> 00:34:02.550 align:middle line:84%
that the limit convergent
sequence in the set.

00:34:02.550 --> 00:34:05.500 align:middle line:84%
Then the limit was
also in the set.

00:34:05.500 --> 00:34:09.699 align:middle line:84%
Now let's prove that
the set is closed.

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:12.139 align:middle line:84%
So to prove the
set is closed, we

00:34:12.139 --> 00:34:16.100 align:middle line:84%
need to show that the
complement is open.

00:34:16.100 --> 00:34:36.369 align:middle line:84%
So we need to show that the
complement here is open.

00:34:36.369 --> 00:34:41.500 align:middle line:90%


00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:48.360 align:middle line:84%
So take x here in
the complement.

00:34:48.360 --> 00:34:56.100 align:middle line:90%


00:34:56.100 --> 00:35:03.700 align:middle line:90%
If for all r greater than 0--

00:35:03.700 --> 00:35:06.810 align:middle line:90%


00:35:06.810 --> 00:35:10.470 align:middle line:90%
so we need to prove that--

00:35:10.470 --> 00:35:13.330 align:middle line:90%
sorry, let me say it like this.

00:35:13.330 --> 00:35:16.210 align:middle line:84%
So we take some x,
and we need to show

00:35:16.210 --> 00:35:26.690 align:middle line:84%
that there exists some
r strictly bigger than 0

00:35:26.690 --> 00:35:33.010 align:middle line:84%
so that this ball here is
contained in the complement.

00:35:33.010 --> 00:35:34.630 align:middle line:90%
That's what we need to prove.

00:35:34.630 --> 00:35:38.210 align:middle line:84%
And we need to prove this
for each x in the complement.

00:35:38.210 --> 00:35:52.970 align:middle line:84%
Now suppose that if
this was not the case,

00:35:52.970 --> 00:35:56.450 align:middle line:90%
then I can look at for each n--

00:35:56.450 --> 00:36:08.880 align:middle line:84%
then for each natural number
here, you can look at the ball.

00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:12.760 align:middle line:84%
It's always going to
be centered at this x.

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:18.640 align:middle line:84%
But I'm looking at it with radii
that is smaller and smaller.

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:24.040 align:middle line:84%
If for each n, natural
number, if that ball

00:36:24.040 --> 00:36:26.360 align:middle line:84%
was not contained
in the complement--

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:29.760 align:middle line:84%
so this means that for
each n, you could pick--

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:34.720 align:middle line:90%
so pick xn in that set.

00:36:34.720 --> 00:36:38.460 align:middle line:90%
So you just choose.

00:36:38.460 --> 00:36:43.380 align:middle line:84%
Because we're assuming that
the complement is not closed.

00:36:43.380 --> 00:36:44.840 align:middle line:90%
It's not open.

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:47.880 align:middle line:84%
So it means that there
would exist at x so

00:36:47.880 --> 00:36:52.500 align:middle line:84%
that no ball here would be
entirely in the complement.

00:36:52.500 --> 00:36:56.800 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this one here
would not be entirely contained

00:36:56.800 --> 00:36:57.700 align:middle line:90%
in complement.

00:36:57.700 --> 00:37:00.830 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
there would be some xn.

00:37:00.830 --> 00:37:10.310 align:middle line:84%
And this xn here would
actually be in the set C.

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:16.830 align:middle line:84%
But now, of course, the
distance here from xn

00:37:16.830 --> 00:37:22.910 align:middle line:84%
to x, this distance here is
strictly less than 1 over n.

00:37:22.910 --> 00:37:25.790 align:middle line:84%
So this means that--
so this implies

00:37:25.790 --> 00:37:30.150 align:middle line:90%
that the xn converges to x.

00:37:30.150 --> 00:37:32.350 align:middle line:84%
And now the assumption
was that whenever

00:37:32.350 --> 00:37:36.670 align:middle line:84%
you have a sequence that was
converging, these guys lie in C.

00:37:36.670 --> 00:37:39.350 align:middle line:84%
Then the limit
here also lie in C.

00:37:39.350 --> 00:37:44.430 align:middle line:84%
So then you have, from the
assumption that x here is in C.

00:37:44.430 --> 00:37:45.810 align:middle line:90%
But this is the contradiction.

00:37:45.810 --> 00:37:51.870 align:middle line:84%
You're assuming
that x was not in C.

00:37:51.870 --> 00:37:58.220 align:middle line:84%
And again, this here is
really, really useful.

00:37:58.220 --> 00:38:02.560 align:middle line:84%
But it's only useful of as
a tool to proving things.

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:06.380 align:middle line:84%
It's not useful for checking
whether an example is

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:07.130 align:middle line:90%
open or closed.

00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:15.220 align:middle line:90%


00:38:15.220 --> 00:38:19.740 align:middle line:84%
Let me just quickly give
you a couple of examples.

00:38:19.740 --> 00:38:21.985 align:middle line:84%
I probably should have
done that already that.

00:38:21.985 --> 00:38:25.380 align:middle line:90%


00:38:25.380 --> 00:38:28.140 align:middle line:90%
If you're looking at--

00:38:28.140 --> 00:38:30.700 align:middle line:90%
so what are closed subsets?

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:34.140 align:middle line:90%
So closed subset could be--

00:38:34.140 --> 00:38:36.660 align:middle line:90%
so here's some examples--

00:38:36.660 --> 00:38:37.530 align:middle line:90%
closed subsets.

00:38:37.530 --> 00:38:42.540 align:middle line:90%


00:38:42.540 --> 00:38:49.420 align:middle line:84%
So if it's an r, a closed
subset is some interval,

00:38:49.420 --> 00:38:54.300 align:middle line:84%
let's say, from 0 to 1,
where both these points are--

00:38:54.300 --> 00:38:55.960 align:middle line:90%
both 0 and 1 is included.

00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:58.650 align:middle line:90%
This has closed.

00:38:58.650 --> 00:38:59.950 align:middle line:90%
And why is it closed?

00:38:59.950 --> 00:39:02.030 align:middle line:84%
Because the complement
here is open.

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:04.350 align:middle line:84%
It's easy to see that
the complement is open.

00:39:04.350 --> 00:39:07.970 align:middle line:90%


00:39:07.970 --> 00:39:11.210 align:middle line:84%
Something like if you
include one of the endpoints

00:39:11.210 --> 00:39:14.720 align:middle line:84%
but not the other, this
is either closed or open.

00:39:14.720 --> 00:39:24.010 align:middle line:90%


00:39:24.010 --> 00:39:28.210 align:middle line:84%
And also, if you're
looking at the complement,

00:39:28.210 --> 00:39:31.210 align:middle line:84%
say, from 0 of the
complement of--

00:39:31.210 --> 00:39:34.930 align:middle line:84%
so if you're looking
at this thing here,

00:39:34.930 --> 00:39:40.660 align:middle line:84%
union, we'll say, from 2
to 3, this is also closed.

00:39:40.660 --> 00:39:49.970 align:middle line:90%


00:39:49.970 --> 00:39:57.290 align:middle line:84%
And maybe one more example is
if you just take a single point,

00:39:57.290 --> 00:39:58.240 align:middle line:90%
this is closed.

00:39:58.240 --> 00:40:02.970 align:middle line:90%


00:40:02.970 --> 00:40:05.650 align:middle line:84%
And again, you just check
that the complement is open.

00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:08.730 align:middle line:90%


00:40:08.730 --> 00:40:14.570 align:middle line:84%
So now the next
thing, which I think

00:40:14.570 --> 00:40:16.730 align:middle line:84%
we talked very briefly
about that last time

00:40:16.730 --> 00:40:19.200 align:middle line:84%
also, because we talked a
little bit about closed subset.

00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:23.083 align:middle line:90%


00:40:23.083 --> 00:40:24.500 align:middle line:84%
So you have the
following theorem.

00:40:24.500 --> 00:40:30.090 align:middle line:90%


00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:33.650 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
metric space here

00:40:33.650 --> 00:40:46.570 align:middle line:84%
and you have a family C
alpha of closed subset,

00:40:46.570 --> 00:40:52.410 align:middle line:84%
then the intersection
of these closed subset,

00:40:52.410 --> 00:40:54.470 align:middle line:90%
this here, is also closed.

00:40:54.470 --> 00:41:00.800 align:middle line:90%


00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:08.360 align:middle line:84%
And if you have just
finitely many closed subset,

00:41:08.360 --> 00:41:16.750 align:middle line:84%
then the union of finitely many
closed subset is also closed.

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:22.000 align:middle line:90%


00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:27.280 align:middle line:84%
And so here, it's exactly the
opposite thing as for open sets

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:30.720 align:middle line:84%
that you can take
any intersection,

00:41:30.720 --> 00:41:33.400 align:middle line:90%
and it's still closed.

00:41:33.400 --> 00:41:36.660 align:middle line:84%
But if you take union, you can
only do it for finitely many.

00:41:36.660 --> 00:41:38.440 align:middle line:90%
So this is exactly the opposite.

00:41:38.440 --> 00:41:40.480 align:middle line:90%
Why is it exactly the opposite?

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:44.500 align:middle line:84%
It's because in order to prove
that something is closed,

00:41:44.500 --> 00:41:47.720 align:middle line:84%
it means that the
complement is open.

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:55.870 align:middle line:84%
And then we have these
basic relations for--

00:41:55.870 --> 00:41:57.600 align:middle line:90%
so the proof of this again.

00:41:57.600 --> 00:42:02.830 align:middle line:90%


00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:05.390 align:middle line:84%
And so these are these
operations on set

00:42:05.390 --> 00:42:10.430 align:middle line:84%
that we went through,
that if you take x here

00:42:10.430 --> 00:42:16.670 align:middle line:84%
and you take the complement
of intersections of subsets.

00:42:16.670 --> 00:42:26.670 align:middle line:84%
This thing here is the same as
the union of the complement,

00:42:26.670 --> 00:42:27.830 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:31.950 align:middle line:84%
And you see that
since this is closed,

00:42:31.950 --> 00:42:34.390 align:middle line:84%
this means that the
complement is open.

00:42:34.390 --> 00:42:37.810 align:middle line:84%
And you can take any union of
open sets, and it's still open.

00:42:37.810 --> 00:42:41.790 align:middle line:84%
So that's why you could
take any intersection.

00:42:41.790 --> 00:42:44.310 align:middle line:84%
And so the other thing
is that if you're

00:42:44.310 --> 00:42:50.220 align:middle line:84%
looking to prove that
this thing here is closed,

00:42:50.220 --> 00:42:54.320 align:middle line:84%
then you're looking at the
complement of this union here.

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:59.020 align:middle line:90%


00:42:59.020 --> 00:43:03.280 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here is
now the intersection,

00:43:03.280 --> 00:43:16.060 align:middle line:84%
the complement of the
intersection of the C1 up to--

00:43:16.060 --> 00:43:21.140 align:middle line:84%
sorry, this is the
complement of-- this

00:43:21.140 --> 00:43:29.880 align:middle line:84%
is the intersection of
these guys, like this.

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:39.860 align:middle line:90%


00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:47.020 align:middle line:84%
And you see here, since C1 up
to Cn, since they are closed,

00:43:47.020 --> 00:43:48.770 align:middle line:90%
these guys here are open.

00:43:48.770 --> 00:43:52.470 align:middle line:84%
And you're looking at finite
intersections of open sets,

00:43:52.470 --> 00:43:53.930 align:middle line:90%
and that's open.

00:43:53.930 --> 00:43:57.530 align:middle line:84%
So again, for closed
sets, in terms

00:43:57.530 --> 00:43:59.570 align:middle line:84%
of taking intersection
and union,

00:43:59.570 --> 00:44:01.230 align:middle line:90%
it's exactly the opposite.

00:44:01.230 --> 00:44:05.280 align:middle line:90%


00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:09.760 align:middle line:84%
Now, the next thing I want
to talk about is a cover.

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:14.290 align:middle line:90%


00:44:14.290 --> 00:44:19.640 align:middle line:90%
So have a metric space.

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:25.130 align:middle line:90%


00:44:25.130 --> 00:44:27.190 align:middle line:90%
So we have a metric space here.

00:44:27.190 --> 00:44:30.090 align:middle line:90%


00:44:30.090 --> 00:44:32.330 align:middle line:90%
And we have a subset--

00:44:32.330 --> 00:44:34.760 align:middle line:90%
A here is a subset of x.

00:44:34.760 --> 00:44:37.690 align:middle line:90%


00:44:37.690 --> 00:44:40.050 align:middle line:90%
And then we have a collection.

00:44:40.050 --> 00:44:55.040 align:middle line:84%
And then you alpha is a
family of subsets of x.

00:44:55.040 --> 00:45:15.600 align:middle line:84%
And we say that u
alpha is a cover of A

00:45:15.600 --> 00:45:24.720 align:middle line:84%
if A is contained in the
union of the u alphas.

00:45:24.720 --> 00:45:30.050 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it means to
cover that set by a family.

00:45:30.050 --> 00:45:35.600 align:middle line:90%


00:45:35.600 --> 00:45:50.480 align:middle line:84%
A subcover of the
cover u alpha is--

00:45:50.480 --> 00:45:52.990 align:middle line:90%


00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:58.070 align:middle line:84%
so imagine that you have
a whole bunch of sets.

00:45:58.070 --> 00:46:02.670 align:middle line:84%
And together, they
cover A sub cover means

00:46:02.670 --> 00:46:06.750 align:middle line:84%
that you don't need to
take all of the u alphas,

00:46:06.750 --> 00:46:08.950 align:middle line:84%
if you can just
take some of them,

00:46:08.950 --> 00:46:12.370 align:middle line:90%
and they will still cover it.

00:46:12.370 --> 00:46:28.190 align:middle line:84%
So a cover is a subfamily
of the given family

00:46:28.190 --> 00:46:45.030 align:middle line:84%
u alpha such that the
union of those still cover.

00:46:45.030 --> 00:46:52.100 align:middle line:90%


00:46:52.100 --> 00:46:57.070 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at a
couple of examples.

00:46:57.070 --> 00:47:02.620 align:middle line:90%


00:47:02.620 --> 00:47:05.460 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if you
take a family that

00:47:05.460 --> 00:47:10.440 align:middle line:84%
covers something, then the
family itself is a subcover.

00:47:10.440 --> 00:47:14.340 align:middle line:84%
But that's a kind
of trivial subcover.

00:47:14.340 --> 00:47:19.800 align:middle line:90%
And so you could look at--

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:23.460 align:middle line:90%
so just here's an example.

00:47:23.460 --> 00:47:28.180 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that the metric space is
x with the usual as r-- sorry,

00:47:28.180 --> 00:47:31.220 align:middle line:90%
with the usual metric.

00:47:31.220 --> 00:47:35.680 align:middle line:84%
And suppose now that the
u alpha is actually Un's,

00:47:35.680 --> 00:47:40.580 align:middle line:84%
and those are integral
from minus n--

00:47:40.580 --> 00:47:41.840 align:middle line:90%
let me just make them open.

00:47:41.840 --> 00:47:42.620 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't matter.

00:47:42.620 --> 00:47:45.740 align:middle line:84%
For a cover, there's no
assertion whether they're

00:47:45.740 --> 00:47:48.500 align:middle line:90%
open or closed or neither.

00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:51.140 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking
at those sets,

00:47:51.140 --> 00:47:55.900 align:middle line:84%
well, if you take the
union of all those sets,

00:47:55.900 --> 00:47:58.020 align:middle line:90%
that gives you everything.

00:47:58.020 --> 00:48:03.220 align:middle line:84%
So this family is a
cover of the real line.

00:48:03.220 --> 00:48:08.680 align:middle line:84%
Of course, if you take a
proper subcover, meaning--

00:48:08.680 --> 00:48:11.020 align:middle line:90%
I mean, well, you could take a--

00:48:11.020 --> 00:48:13.780 align:middle line:90%
so this here cover all of it.

00:48:13.780 --> 00:48:16.220 align:middle line:84%
But you see that this
particular cover has

00:48:16.220 --> 00:48:21.060 align:middle line:90%
the property that Un plus 1--

00:48:21.060 --> 00:48:25.300 align:middle line:84%
this is contained,
the previous one.

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:31.860 align:middle line:84%
So you don't really need
all of them to cover r.

00:48:31.860 --> 00:48:35.820 align:middle line:84%
If you wanted to, you could
start with some very large n,

00:48:35.820 --> 00:48:38.220 align:middle line:84%
and then you could
go on from there.

00:48:38.220 --> 00:48:43.890 align:middle line:84%
But there wouldn't be finitely
many of the Un that would cover.

00:48:43.890 --> 00:48:48.690 align:middle line:84%
You need infinite money to
cover because, otherwise, there

00:48:48.690 --> 00:48:53.740 align:middle line:84%
would be some of last
point and both interest.

00:48:53.740 --> 00:48:56.430 align:middle line:90%


00:48:56.430 --> 00:49:00.370 align:middle line:84%
So that's a cover
and a subcover.

00:49:00.370 --> 00:49:14.210 align:middle line:84%
And an open cover
is, then, where

00:49:14.210 --> 00:49:21.000 align:middle line:90%
each u alpha is an open subset.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:29.570 align:middle line:90%


00:49:29.570 --> 00:49:33.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you it's
really distinct that--

00:49:33.070 --> 00:49:40.680 align:middle line:90%


00:49:40.680 --> 00:49:42.480 align:middle line:90%
so that's our open cover.

00:49:42.480 --> 00:49:48.480 align:middle line:84%
So each of the sets that is in
the covering has to be open.

00:49:48.480 --> 00:50:03.840 align:middle line:84%
And the last definition we
need is a finite subcover

00:50:03.840 --> 00:50:15.900 align:middle line:84%
is a subcover consisting
of finite sets.

00:50:15.900 --> 00:50:26.880 align:middle line:90%


00:50:26.880 --> 00:50:28.850 align:middle line:90%
So that's a finite subcover.

00:50:28.850 --> 00:50:31.520 align:middle line:90%


00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:35.560 align:middle line:90%
And so now this leads to the--

00:50:35.560 --> 00:50:43.510 align:middle line:84%
and again, in this example here,
r where this here is a cover,

00:50:43.510 --> 00:50:45.050 align:middle line:90%
there is no finite--

00:50:45.050 --> 00:51:04.630 align:middle line:84%
so note that this
particular cover does not

00:51:04.630 --> 00:51:06.180 align:middle line:90%
have a finite subcover.

00:51:06.180 --> 00:51:14.390 align:middle line:90%


00:51:14.390 --> 00:51:16.950 align:middle line:84%
If you just take
finitely many of these,

00:51:16.950 --> 00:51:19.910 align:middle line:84%
they are not going
to cover all of r.

00:51:19.910 --> 00:51:21.510 align:middle line:84%
But actually, in
this example, you

00:51:21.510 --> 00:51:25.210 align:middle line:84%
see also that the
cover is an open cover.

00:51:25.210 --> 00:51:28.130 align:middle line:90%


00:51:28.130 --> 00:51:34.950 align:middle line:84%
So this now leads to the
definition of compactness.

00:51:34.950 --> 00:51:39.770 align:middle line:90%
So you have a metric space.

00:51:39.770 --> 00:51:47.540 align:middle line:90%


00:51:47.540 --> 00:51:52.580 align:middle line:90%
So x comma d is a metric space.

00:51:52.580 --> 00:51:55.140 align:middle line:90%
A here is a subset.

00:51:55.140 --> 00:52:44.170 align:middle line:84%
And we say that A is compact
if for every open cover of A

00:52:44.170 --> 00:52:46.000 align:middle line:90%
there is a finite subcover.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:53:05.530 align:middle line:90%


00:53:05.530 --> 00:53:10.810 align:middle line:84%
And the thing that
is really useful is--

00:53:10.810 --> 00:53:19.530 align:middle line:84%
and we won't prove this today,
but I'll prove it next time.

00:53:19.530 --> 00:53:30.840 align:middle line:84%
So this is the following result.
So why is this notion useful?

00:53:30.840 --> 00:53:35.080 align:middle line:90%


00:53:35.080 --> 00:53:38.360 align:middle line:84%
So one of the key
properties, when

00:53:38.360 --> 00:53:40.840 align:middle line:84%
you're thinking
about sequences, one

00:53:40.840 --> 00:53:46.320 align:middle line:84%
of the key properties
for sequences on the line

00:53:46.320 --> 00:53:50.900 align:middle line:84%
was the Cauchy
convergence theorem.

00:53:50.900 --> 00:53:52.420 align:middle line:84%
And the Cauchy
convergence theorem,

00:53:52.420 --> 00:53:54.780 align:middle line:84%
again, said that whenever
you have a Cauchy sequence,

00:53:54.780 --> 00:53:56.900 align:middle line:84%
then it was
automatically convergent,

00:53:56.900 --> 00:54:00.280 align:middle line:84%
and it was often much easier
to check that a sequence was

00:54:00.280 --> 00:54:03.880 align:middle line:84%
a Cauchy sequence than to
actually find the limit

00:54:03.880 --> 00:54:07.800 align:middle line:84%
and prove that it's
converging to that.

00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:10.300 align:middle line:84%
But to prove the Cauchy
convergence theorem,

00:54:10.300 --> 00:54:12.840 align:middle line:84%
we needed the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:54:12.840 --> 00:54:16.940 align:middle line:90%
And so this is because--

00:54:16.940 --> 00:54:20.240 align:middle line:84%
so why is it useful, this
notion of compactness?

00:54:20.240 --> 00:54:28.480 align:middle line:84%
So it's useful because
there's a metric version

00:54:28.480 --> 00:54:48.030 align:middle line:84%
of the Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem for metric spaces.

00:54:48.030 --> 00:54:53.360 align:middle line:90%


00:54:53.360 --> 00:54:57.160 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
following theorem.

00:54:57.160 --> 00:55:00.960 align:middle line:84%
And again, I won't prove it now,
but I'll prove it next time,

00:55:00.960 --> 00:55:09.640 align:middle line:84%
that if you take a metric
space, and A here is a subset

00:55:09.640 --> 00:55:30.552 align:middle line:84%
and A is compact,
then any sequence in A

00:55:30.552 --> 00:55:37.070 align:middle line:90%
has a convergent subsequence.

00:55:37.070 --> 00:55:43.890 align:middle line:90%


00:55:43.890 --> 00:55:45.950 align:middle line:84%
So remember that the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem,

00:55:45.950 --> 00:55:54.870 align:middle line:84%
again, said that if you take
an upper bounded sequence in r,

00:55:54.870 --> 00:55:58.160 align:middle line:84%
then there is a
subsequence that converge.

00:55:58.160 --> 00:56:01.110 align:middle line:90%


00:56:01.110 --> 00:56:08.440 align:middle line:84%
So now let's prove
a few things about--

00:56:08.440 --> 00:56:14.790 align:middle line:90%


00:56:14.790 --> 00:56:18.990 align:middle line:84%
and let me also look at a
couple of more examples.

00:56:18.990 --> 00:56:25.190 align:middle line:84%
So the first thing I want
to just discuss is that--

00:56:25.190 --> 00:56:27.250 align:middle line:90%
so this here is the key--

00:56:27.250 --> 00:56:30.860 align:middle line:84%
this is our key
application of compactness

00:56:30.860 --> 00:56:32.580 align:middle line:84%
that you have this
metric version

00:56:32.580 --> 00:56:34.480 align:middle line:84%
of the Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem.

00:56:34.480 --> 00:56:47.580 align:middle line:90%


00:56:47.580 --> 00:56:53.940 align:middle line:84%
But let's prove a couple of
things about compact subsets.

00:56:53.940 --> 00:56:56.760 align:middle line:90%
So we have a metric space here.

00:56:56.760 --> 00:57:00.420 align:middle line:90%


00:57:00.420 --> 00:57:07.650 align:middle line:90%
And I have A here is compact.

00:57:07.650 --> 00:57:12.340 align:middle line:90%


00:57:12.340 --> 00:57:17.780 align:middle line:84%
Then I want to show that
this implies two things.

00:57:17.780 --> 00:57:20.510 align:middle line:90%
One is that A is bounded.

00:57:20.510 --> 00:57:28.810 align:middle line:90%


00:57:28.810 --> 00:57:31.780 align:middle line:84%
And the second one
is that A is closed.

00:57:31.780 --> 00:57:41.610 align:middle line:90%


00:57:41.610 --> 00:57:43.940 align:middle line:84%
Let's prove first
that A is bounded.

00:57:43.940 --> 00:58:00.430 align:middle line:90%


00:58:00.430 --> 00:58:04.690 align:middle line:84%
So you could look at a
very trivial cover of A.

00:58:04.690 --> 00:58:13.810 align:middle line:84%
So you have here
A. Well, obviously,

00:58:13.810 --> 00:58:20.530 align:middle line:84%
if you take all balls,
let's say, with radius 1,

00:58:20.530 --> 00:58:24.480 align:middle line:84%
and you take all balls,
but now the center

00:58:24.480 --> 00:58:30.920 align:middle line:90%
here could be anything in A.

00:58:30.920 --> 00:58:36.400 align:middle line:84%
For each element in A, you
take a ball of radius 1

00:58:36.400 --> 00:58:38.720 align:middle line:90%
around that point.

00:58:38.720 --> 00:58:42.360 align:middle line:84%
But first of all, these
balls are all open.

00:58:42.360 --> 00:58:46.340 align:middle line:84%
And of course, this thing
here, the union of these guys,

00:58:46.340 --> 00:58:49.140 align:middle line:84%
well, the union contains, in
particular, all the centers,

00:58:49.140 --> 00:58:55.400 align:middle line:84%
but the centers is already A.
So you trivially have this.

00:58:55.400 --> 00:59:06.720 align:middle line:84%
Now since A is
compact, this means

00:59:06.720 --> 00:59:11.100 align:middle line:84%
that A must be that
this is an open cover.

00:59:11.100 --> 00:59:16.840 align:middle line:84%
So it means that finitely
many of them already cover A,

00:59:16.840 --> 00:59:25.410 align:middle line:84%
so you have finitely
many, like this.

00:59:25.410 --> 00:59:30.750 align:middle line:84%
But now I claim that
this automatically

00:59:30.750 --> 00:59:35.470 align:middle line:84%
implies that A is
bounded because, you see,

00:59:35.470 --> 00:59:39.110 align:middle line:90%
you have all these balls here.

00:59:39.110 --> 00:59:43.010 align:middle line:84%
And A is somehow contained
in the union of these guys.

00:59:43.010 --> 00:59:46.850 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
for any element--

00:59:46.850 --> 00:59:49.350 align:middle line:90%
so this means that for any x--

00:59:49.350 --> 01:00:00.910 align:middle line:84%
so if x here is in
A, then there exists

01:00:00.910 --> 01:00:06.110 align:middle line:84%
one of these finitely many i,
where i is one of these finitely

01:00:06.110 --> 01:00:10.510 align:middle line:90%
many so that the distance.

01:00:10.510 --> 01:00:16.030 align:middle line:90%
to this xi is smaller than 1.

01:00:16.030 --> 01:00:20.230 align:middle line:84%
We would like to say that a
is contained in a large ball.

01:00:20.230 --> 01:00:36.820 align:middle line:90%


01:00:36.820 --> 01:00:42.580 align:middle line:84%
Now you just pick
one of these xi's.

01:00:42.580 --> 01:00:45.200 align:middle line:90%
Let's pick the first one.

01:00:45.200 --> 01:00:52.050 align:middle line:84%
And let's look at the
maximum of these--

01:00:52.050 --> 01:00:54.740 align:middle line:90%


01:00:54.740 --> 01:00:57.530 align:middle line:84%
from the first one
to the other one.

01:00:57.530 --> 01:01:02.580 align:middle line:90%


01:01:02.580 --> 01:01:05.820 align:middle line:90%
And let's add 1 to that.

01:01:05.820 --> 01:01:10.160 align:middle line:84%
You take the maximum of
finitely many numbers.

01:01:10.160 --> 01:01:13.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is a nice
finitely many numbers.

01:01:13.380 --> 01:01:17.340 align:middle line:90%
And you call this here r.

01:01:17.340 --> 01:01:24.290 align:middle line:84%
Now you look at the ball
of radius r around x1.

01:01:24.290 --> 01:01:26.710 align:middle line:90%
And I want to show that any x--

01:01:26.710 --> 01:01:29.270 align:middle line:90%


01:01:29.270 --> 01:01:44.650 align:middle line:84%
so I want to show
That for any x in A,

01:01:44.650 --> 01:01:50.790 align:middle line:84%
then we have that x is
in this ball, like that.

01:01:50.790 --> 01:02:15.510 align:middle line:90%


01:02:15.510 --> 01:02:21.490 align:middle line:84%
So now we know that--
so since x here is,

01:02:21.490 --> 01:02:25.670 align:middle line:84%
we know that x is contained
in the union of this ball.

01:02:25.670 --> 01:02:36.650 align:middle line:84%
So we know that x is contained
in this ball here for some i,

01:02:36.650 --> 01:02:40.330 align:middle line:84%
where it's one of these
little n many i's.

01:02:40.330 --> 01:02:42.850 align:middle line:90%


01:02:42.850 --> 01:02:47.010 align:middle line:84%
So this means now
that the distance--

01:02:47.010 --> 01:02:53.410 align:middle line:84%
and so you know that the
distance to this little i

01:02:53.410 --> 01:02:54.850 align:middle line:90%
is at most 1.

01:02:54.850 --> 01:02:58.250 align:middle line:84%
And so now if you're
looking at the distance

01:02:58.250 --> 01:03:02.250 align:middle line:84%
from x to the first
one, then this here

01:03:02.250 --> 01:03:09.930 align:middle line:84%
is less than the
distance from this to xi

01:03:09.930 --> 01:03:14.810 align:middle line:84%
plus the distance-- this is the
triangle inequality again xi.

01:03:14.810 --> 01:03:16.640 align:middle line:84%
Maybe let me just
make very clear

01:03:16.640 --> 01:03:21.360 align:middle line:84%
that this is the first
one to the first one.

01:03:21.360 --> 01:03:24.160 align:middle line:90%
This is the triangle inequality.

01:03:24.160 --> 01:03:28.360 align:middle line:90%
But these distances here are--

01:03:28.360 --> 01:03:41.920 align:middle line:90%


01:03:41.920 --> 01:03:44.600 align:middle line:84%
this thing here
is bounded by $1.

01:03:44.600 --> 01:03:49.120 align:middle line:84%
It's actually
strictly less than 1.

01:03:49.120 --> 01:03:53.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is less than 1
plus this thing here.

01:03:53.420 --> 01:03:57.520 align:middle line:90%


01:03:57.520 --> 01:04:00.520 align:middle line:84%
And you see, this thing
here is, of course, this

01:04:00.520 --> 01:04:04.000 align:middle line:90%
is how we define r.

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:08.560 align:middle line:84%
This is actually less
than or equal to r.

01:04:08.560 --> 01:04:13.703 align:middle line:84%
And so you have this thing
here is strictly less than r.

01:04:13.703 --> 01:04:15.370 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we
want wanted to prove.

01:04:15.370 --> 01:04:18.810 align:middle line:90%


01:04:18.810 --> 01:04:22.950 align:middle line:84%
So this proves that if you take,
again, a metric space and you

01:04:22.950 --> 01:04:28.230 align:middle line:84%
have a compact subset, then
it's automatically bounded.

01:04:28.230 --> 01:04:29.870 align:middle line:90%
What about the second one?

01:04:29.870 --> 01:04:33.430 align:middle line:90%
Suppose you take a subset.

01:04:33.430 --> 01:04:35.990 align:middle line:90%
Is it closed?

01:04:35.990 --> 01:04:38.780 align:middle line:84%
Now let's use the theorem
that we just proved.

01:04:38.780 --> 01:04:45.270 align:middle line:90%


01:04:45.270 --> 01:04:46.460 align:middle line:90%
So we need to prove--

01:04:46.460 --> 01:05:01.110 align:middle line:90%


01:05:01.110 --> 01:05:05.940 align:middle line:84%
so let's prove that
this A here is closed.

01:05:05.940 --> 01:05:23.460 align:middle line:90%


01:05:23.460 --> 01:05:27.200 align:middle line:90%
So now if A is closed--

01:05:27.200 --> 01:05:40.460 align:middle line:84%
so to prove that A is
closed by the theorem

01:05:40.460 --> 01:05:43.120 align:middle line:84%
we just proved just
a little while ago--

01:05:43.120 --> 01:05:46.140 align:middle line:90%


01:05:46.140 --> 01:05:53.740 align:middle line:84%
theorem we proved
earlier, we need

01:05:53.740 --> 01:06:08.620 align:middle line:84%
to show that if xn is a sequence
in A and xn is converging

01:06:08.620 --> 01:06:36.930 align:middle line:84%
to some x, we need to
show that x is also in A.

01:06:36.930 --> 01:06:41.370 align:middle line:84%
Suppose now we want to show that
this leads to a contradiction.

01:06:41.370 --> 01:06:42.990 align:middle line:90%
We want to get a contradiction.

01:06:42.990 --> 01:06:54.050 align:middle line:90%


01:06:54.050 --> 01:06:57.650 align:middle line:90%
So you have this x here.

01:06:57.650 --> 01:07:02.390 align:middle line:84%
And you're assuming
that x is not in A.

01:07:02.390 --> 01:07:11.400 align:middle line:84%
Yet you have a sequence in A
that somehow tends to this--

01:07:11.400 --> 01:07:14.670 align:middle line:84%
this is the sequence xn, and
it's heading to this element.

01:07:14.670 --> 01:07:19.520 align:middle line:90%


01:07:19.520 --> 01:07:31.540 align:middle line:84%
Well, we saw earlier that we
define something called E here,

01:07:31.540 --> 01:07:42.680 align:middle line:84%
which is the x, the y in x, so
that the distance from x to y

01:07:42.680 --> 01:07:45.080 align:middle line:90%
is strictly bigger than r.

01:07:45.080 --> 01:07:48.940 align:middle line:84%
Then we saw that this
here is an open set.

01:07:48.940 --> 01:07:51.800 align:middle line:90%
We show that this is open.

01:07:51.800 --> 01:07:55.320 align:middle line:90%
This is for each r.

01:07:55.320 --> 01:08:02.880 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to now
find a cover of A. I'm

01:08:02.880 --> 01:08:05.040 align:middle line:90%
going to find an open cover.

01:08:05.040 --> 01:08:13.550 align:middle line:84%
And the open cover is that for
each integer, for each n here,

01:08:13.550 --> 01:08:18.710 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to look at E 1 over n.

01:08:18.710 --> 01:08:23.710 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
I'm looking at the y

01:08:23.710 --> 01:08:30.430 align:middle line:84%
so that the distance from y to
this x here that I want to show

01:08:30.430 --> 01:08:37.370 align:middle line:84%
is an A, that this thing
here is bigger than 1 over n.

01:08:37.370 --> 01:08:41.950 align:middle line:90%


01:08:41.950 --> 01:08:48.750 align:middle line:84%
But now I claim
that A is contained

01:08:48.750 --> 01:08:59.630 align:middle line:84%
in the union of these
guys because, you see,

01:08:59.630 --> 01:09:06.830 align:middle line:84%
actually, these guys here, if
you have something that is not

01:09:06.830 --> 01:09:14.910 align:middle line:84%
in any of these, this means
that this inequality fails

01:09:14.910 --> 01:09:20.910 align:middle line:84%
with each n, but this
means that-- so if set

01:09:20.910 --> 01:09:30.310 align:middle line:84%
is in the complement of
the union of these guys,

01:09:30.310 --> 01:09:33.229 align:middle line:84%
actually, then you
have that this thing

01:09:33.229 --> 01:09:39.810 align:middle line:84%
here is less than or equal
to 1 over n for all n.

01:09:39.810 --> 01:09:43.149 align:middle line:90%


01:09:43.149 --> 01:09:44.430 align:middle line:90%
You have that.

01:09:44.430 --> 01:09:47.750 align:middle line:84%
That's a complement
of the union.

01:09:47.750 --> 01:09:50.630 align:middle line:84%
But if it's less than
1 over n for all n,

01:09:50.630 --> 01:09:51.860 align:middle line:90%
it means that it must be 0.

01:09:51.860 --> 01:09:54.510 align:middle line:90%


01:09:54.510 --> 01:09:57.030 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this distance here--

01:09:57.030 --> 01:10:01.610 align:middle line:84%
so you conclude that
this distance is 0.

01:10:01.610 --> 01:10:07.580 align:middle line:84%
But this means that this
set here is actually your x.

01:10:07.580 --> 01:10:11.740 align:middle line:84%
So the complement of
these guys, the complement

01:10:11.740 --> 01:10:15.980 align:middle line:84%
of this union here is
simply just a point x.

01:10:15.980 --> 01:10:18.460 align:middle line:84%
But you are assuming
that x was not

01:10:18.460 --> 01:10:24.100 align:middle line:84%
in your set A. The complement
here, the union of these guys,

01:10:24.100 --> 01:10:29.740 align:middle line:84%
we have proved now that the
union covers everything but x.

01:10:29.740 --> 01:10:32.740 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, it covers
A because we're assuming

01:10:32.740 --> 01:10:38.700 align:middle line:90%
that little x was not in A.

01:10:38.700 --> 01:10:44.460 align:middle line:84%
So this is a nice
open cover of A.

01:10:44.460 --> 01:10:46.980 align:middle line:84%
But A was supposed
to be compact.

01:10:46.980 --> 01:10:49.360 align:middle line:84%
It means that finitely
many of these cover.

01:10:49.360 --> 01:10:52.540 align:middle line:90%


01:10:52.540 --> 01:11:03.100 align:middle line:84%
But now this family has
this property that you see--

01:11:03.100 --> 01:11:09.370 align:middle line:84%
these guys here, if you're
looking at E 1 over n,

01:11:09.370 --> 01:11:17.650 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is contained
in E 1 over n plus 1.

01:11:17.650 --> 01:11:21.170 align:middle line:84%
If this number here
is smaller, then it

01:11:21.170 --> 01:11:25.610 align:middle line:84%
means that this
set here is larger.

01:11:25.610 --> 01:11:27.330 align:middle line:90%
So you have this--

01:11:27.330 --> 01:11:30.890 align:middle line:84%
and so you see that
if finitely many--

01:11:30.890 --> 01:11:36.690 align:middle line:84%
if A here was contained in
finitely many of these guys

01:11:36.690 --> 01:11:52.010 align:middle line:84%
here, if it was contained
in a union of finitely many,

01:11:52.010 --> 01:11:57.250 align:middle line:84%
then you just take one of
these n that is the largest.

01:11:57.250 --> 01:12:03.000 align:middle line:84%
So this means that A here
would be contained in some 1

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:10.060 align:middle line:84%
over for some i because
there's one of these numbers--

01:12:10.060 --> 01:12:13.400 align:middle line:84%
these ni's, that
would be the largest.

01:12:13.400 --> 01:12:19.640 align:middle line:90%
But this means now that A--

01:12:19.640 --> 01:12:28.640 align:middle line:84%
that there is some lower bound
for the distance to x in A.

01:12:28.640 --> 01:12:30.760 align:middle line:90%
There's no elements that is--

01:12:30.760 --> 01:12:35.640 align:middle line:84%
so this means that
there exists--

01:12:35.640 --> 01:12:48.880 align:middle line:84%
that does not exist, let
me say, for all y in A.

01:12:48.880 --> 01:12:58.680 align:middle line:84%
Then the distance here from y
to x is strictly bigger than 1

01:12:58.680 --> 01:13:02.110 align:middle line:90%
over this in i.

01:13:02.110 --> 01:13:04.870 align:middle line:90%
This is just some fixed number.

01:13:04.870 --> 01:13:07.430 align:middle line:84%
This is obviously
po-- you know, right?

01:13:07.430 --> 01:13:11.870 align:middle line:84%
But this means that you can't
have a sequence in A that

01:13:11.870 --> 01:13:18.890 align:middle line:84%
is converging to x because
they all stay away from x.

01:13:18.890 --> 01:13:23.450 align:middle line:84%
They stay a certain
distance away from x.

01:13:23.450 --> 01:13:26.190 align:middle line:90%


01:13:26.190 --> 01:13:28.830 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
desired contradiction.

01:13:28.830 --> 01:13:49.510 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, there is no sequence
that converges to x and the xn

01:13:49.510 --> 01:13:50.470 align:middle line:90%
on A.

01:13:50.470 --> 01:13:54.470 align:middle line:84%
But that's what we
assumed in the beginning.

01:13:54.470 --> 01:13:55.830 align:middle line:90%
We wanted to check.

01:13:55.830 --> 01:14:00.980 align:middle line:84%
Then whenever you
have a sequence in An

01:14:00.980 --> 01:14:05.660 align:middle line:84%
that is converging,
then the limit was also.

01:14:05.660 --> 01:14:08.280 align:middle line:84%
So that was supposed to
have been such a sequence.

01:14:08.280 --> 01:14:11.220 align:middle line:84%
So that's a desired
contradiction.

01:14:11.220 --> 01:14:17.900 align:middle line:84%
So this proved that if you take
a compact metric space, then

01:14:17.900 --> 01:14:23.300 align:middle line:84%
if you take a metric space and
if you take a compact subset,

01:14:23.300 --> 01:14:26.380 align:middle line:84%
the compact subset could,
of course, be all of x.

01:14:26.380 --> 01:14:26.990 align:middle line:90%
That's fine.

01:14:26.990 --> 01:14:30.620 align:middle line:90%


01:14:30.620 --> 01:14:33.380 align:middle line:84%
But I want to allow
more generally that just

01:14:33.380 --> 01:14:36.540 align:middle line:84%
to say that just having
a subset that is compact,

01:14:36.540 --> 01:14:39.780 align:middle line:84%
this means that it's
bounded and closed.

01:14:39.780 --> 01:14:41.510 align:middle line:90%
If you are in Rn--

01:14:41.510 --> 01:14:44.620 align:middle line:90%


01:14:44.620 --> 01:14:51.660 align:middle line:84%
so you have a theorem, and we'll
talk about that next time also,

01:14:51.660 --> 01:14:52.820 align:middle line:90%
that this theorem--

01:14:52.820 --> 01:14:55.820 align:middle line:84%
let's say the
converse is the case.

01:14:55.820 --> 01:14:59.050 align:middle line:90%
But that is not actually--

01:14:59.050 --> 01:15:02.130 align:middle line:84%
that does not generalize
to metric spaces.

01:15:02.130 --> 01:15:04.970 align:middle line:90%
So it says theorem here.

01:15:04.970 --> 01:15:09.330 align:middle line:84%
Well, I mean it does
generalize, but not like this.

01:15:09.330 --> 01:15:13.890 align:middle line:84%
This particular
statement does not hold.

01:15:13.890 --> 01:15:23.050 align:middle line:84%
So in Rn with the usual metric,
say the usual Euclidean metric,

01:15:23.050 --> 01:15:23.550 align:middle line:90%
if you will.

01:15:23.550 --> 01:15:29.970 align:middle line:84%
You can just think
about R. If A is

01:15:29.970 --> 01:15:42.020 align:middle line:84%
compact is closed and
bounded, then A is compact.

01:15:42.020 --> 01:15:46.010 align:middle line:90%


01:15:46.010 --> 01:15:50.950 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to talk
about an example,

01:15:50.950 --> 01:15:54.010 align:middle line:84%
but I don't think
I have enough time

01:15:54.010 --> 01:15:59.220 align:middle line:90%
to actually talk about that.

01:15:59.220 --> 01:16:03.525 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about this--
return to this next time

01:16:03.525 --> 01:16:05.150 align:middle line:84%
because we only have
four minutes left.

01:16:05.150 --> 01:16:10.840 align:middle line:90%


01:16:10.840 --> 01:16:19.794 align:middle line:84%
And so, instead, let's
prove a theorem here that--

01:16:19.794 --> 01:16:22.640 align:middle line:90%


01:16:22.640 --> 01:16:28.960 align:middle line:84%
if we take the theorem, if
you have a metric space,

01:16:28.960 --> 01:16:35.840 align:middle line:84%
A here is a subset
of x is compact,

01:16:35.840 --> 01:16:43.860 align:middle line:84%
suppose that C here is a subset
of A and C here is [INAUDIBLE].

01:16:43.860 --> 01:16:45.140 align:middle line:90%
So this is, of course, in x.

01:16:45.140 --> 01:16:47.400 align:middle line:90%
So C is also a subset of x.

01:16:47.400 --> 01:16:51.800 align:middle line:90%
And C is closed.

01:16:51.800 --> 01:16:57.170 align:middle line:84%
Then the claim is that
then C is also compact.

01:16:57.170 --> 01:17:02.440 align:middle line:90%


01:17:02.440 --> 01:17:04.040 align:middle line:84%
And we have three
minutes, and we

01:17:04.040 --> 01:17:08.080 align:middle line:84%
don't need three minutes because
it's actually very quick.

01:17:08.080 --> 01:17:11.480 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is--
so proof of this--

01:17:11.480 --> 01:17:15.280 align:middle line:84%
so C here is assumed
to be closed.

01:17:15.280 --> 01:17:22.200 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
since C is closed,

01:17:22.200 --> 01:17:26.450 align:middle line:84%
this means that the
complement of C is open.

01:17:26.450 --> 01:17:34.400 align:middle line:90%


01:17:34.400 --> 01:17:51.340 align:middle line:84%
So now let's let O
alpha be a cover of C.

01:17:51.340 --> 01:17:54.190 align:middle line:84%
So O alpha is a cover
of C, and now you

01:17:54.190 --> 01:17:58.430 align:middle line:84%
can add the
complement of C to it.

01:17:58.430 --> 01:18:02.990 align:middle line:90%
So if you're looking at C--

01:18:02.990 --> 01:18:11.070 align:middle line:84%
so C here is now,
of course, in fact,

01:18:11.070 --> 01:18:16.910 align:middle line:84%
A here, you can think about
A as-- so A is clearly

01:18:16.910 --> 01:18:28.110 align:middle line:84%
contained in C union
with the complement of C.

01:18:28.110 --> 01:18:34.650 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that A
here, the O alpha cover C--

01:18:34.650 --> 01:18:39.350 align:middle line:84%
so this is contained in
the union of O alpha union

01:18:39.350 --> 01:18:41.510 align:middle line:90%
with this last set.

01:18:41.510 --> 01:18:44.190 align:middle line:90%


01:18:44.190 --> 01:18:46.950 align:middle line:84%
These guys are
assumed to be open.

01:18:46.950 --> 01:18:49.950 align:middle line:84%
This here is open
because C is closed.

01:18:49.950 --> 01:18:54.220 align:middle line:84%
So this means that you have
now A is contained in--

01:18:54.220 --> 01:18:58.260 align:middle line:84%
this is an open cover of A. So
this means that finitely many

01:18:58.260 --> 01:18:59.840 align:middle line:90%
of these--

01:18:59.840 --> 01:19:04.620 align:middle line:84%
so this means that A is
contained in like O1 union

01:19:04.620 --> 01:19:06.460 align:middle line:90%
up to some On.

01:19:06.460 --> 01:19:11.900 align:middle line:84%
And then, quite possibly, you
would also need this one here.

01:19:11.900 --> 01:19:16.540 align:middle line:84%
But now you see, but C
here is contained in here.

01:19:16.540 --> 01:19:19.780 align:middle line:84%
So this means that C
is contained in this.

01:19:19.780 --> 01:19:22.460 align:middle line:84%
This here was not
part of the cover,

01:19:22.460 --> 01:19:26.340 align:middle line:84%
but it's not needed if you just
want to cover C because none

01:19:26.340 --> 01:19:30.780 align:middle line:84%
of these elements
cover anything in C.

01:19:30.780 --> 01:19:36.900 align:middle line:84%
So this implies that C actually
must be contained in O1 union

01:19:36.900 --> 01:19:42.020 align:middle line:84%
up to On because this here does
not cover anything in C. So

01:19:42.020 --> 01:19:44.100 align:middle line:90%
this proves that C--

01:19:44.100 --> 01:19:47.790 align:middle line:84%
there was a finite
subcover that covers C.

01:19:47.790 --> 01:19:50.000 align:middle line:90%